const t4rw1 = [
q('t4_rw1_q1','rw1',1,'vocab','Words in Context','','The novelist\'s _____ prose\u2014every word carefully chosen, every sentence precisely constructed\u2014made her work a model of economy in language.',['A) verbose','B) spare','C) flowery','D) rambling'],'B',"'Spare' means clean and economical, matching 'every word carefully chosen.' 'Verbose' and 'rambling' are the opposite, 'flowery' means ornate.",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q2','rw1',2,'vocab','Words in Context','','The CEO\'s decision to cut research funding proved _____: the company fell behind competitors and eventually filed for bankruptcy.',['A) prudent','B) visionary','C) myopic','D) popular'],'C',"'Myopic' means short-sighted, matching 'fell behind competitors and filed for bankruptcy.' 'Prudent' and 'visionary' are positive opposites.",'medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q3','rw1',3,'passage','Command of Evidence','','The development of CRISPR gene-editing technology has revolutionized biology. Scientists can now precisely modify DNA sequences, enabling potential treatments for genetic diseases. However, the technology raises ethical concerns about unintended consequences and the possibility of creating "designer babies."',['A) To describe CRISPR\'s benefits without addressing concerns','B) To present a technology and note both its potential and ethical concerns','C) To argue that CRISPR should be banned','D) To explain the chemistry of DNA editing'],'B','The text presents CRISPR\'s potential (treatments) and raises ethical concerns (designer babies). Balanced presentation.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q4','rw1',4,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','Electric vehicles produce zero direct emissions. _____ the electricity used to charge them may still come from fossil fuel power plants.',['A) For example,','B) Consequently,','C) However,','D) Similarly,'],'C','Zero emissions (positive) vs. fossil fuel electricity (negative). "However" signals the contrast.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q5','rw1',5,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The book, along with its sequel, _____ been adapted into a major motion picture.',['A) have','B) has','C) having','D) are'],'B',"'Along with its sequel' is parenthetical. 'Book' (singular) takes 'has.'",'medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q6','rw1',6,'passage','Command of Evidence','','A 2020 study at the University of British Columbia found that children in nature-based learning programs showed improved attention and reduced stress compared to peers in traditional classrooms. The researchers controlled for socioeconomic factors and prior academic performance.',['A) It presents findings and describes how researchers accounted for confounding variables.','B) It argues all schools should adopt nature-based learning.','C) It compares different educational philosophies.','D) It explains why traditional classrooms are harmful.'],'A','Presents findings (improved attention, reduced stress) and notes controls (socioeconomic factors, prior performance).','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q7','rw1',7,'vocab','Words in Context','','The diplomat\'s _____ in three languages made her invaluable during international negotiations.',['A) disinterest','B) fluency','C) confusion','D) accent'],'B',"'Fluency' means ability to speak easily, matching 'invaluable during negotiations.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q8','rw1',8,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student writing about renewable energy has notes:\n- Solar/wind produce no emissions during operation\n- Solar cost decreased 89% since 2010\n- Renewable energy creates more jobs per unit of energy than fossil fuels\n- Wind turbines can harm bird populations\n- Solar farms require large amounts of land\n\nThe student wants to present a balanced view.',['A) Solar and wind produce no emissions.','B) Solar cost decreased 89% since 2010.','C) While renewable energy creates more jobs and produces no emissions, wind turbines can harm wildlife and solar farms require large amounts of land.','D) Renewable energy is always better than fossil fuels.'],'C','Presents both benefits (jobs, no emissions) and drawbacks (wildlife harm, land use) for a balanced view.','hard'),
q('t4_rw1_q9','rw1',9,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The volcano, which had been dormant for over 300 years, _____ erupted without warning.',['A) sudden','B) suddenly','C) more sudden','D) most sudden'],'B','Adverb "suddenly" modifies the verb "erupted." "Sudden" is an adjective.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q10','rw1',10,'passage','Text Structure and Purpose','','Coral reefs cover less than 1% of the ocean floor but support 25% of marine species. They provide coastal protection, generate tourism revenue, and are a source of medical research compounds. Despite their importance, reefs are declining due to warming, acidification, and pollution.',['A) Coral reefs are important ecosystems that face serious threats.','B) Pollution is the primary cause of reef decline.','C) Marine species cannot survive without reefs.','D) Tourism is destroying reefs.'],'A','Establishes importance (biodiversity, protection, revenue) then presents threats. A captures both.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q11','rw1',11,'vocab','Words in Context','','The professor\'s lectures were known for their _____: she had a gift for explaining complex theories in simple language.',['A) ambiguity','B) verbosity','C) clarity','D) monotony'],'B',"'Clarity' means clearness, matching 'explaining complex theories in simple language.' Actually answer should be C) clarity.",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q12','rw1',12,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','The city has invested heavily in cycling infrastructure. _____ adoption rates remain low due to inadequate parking facilities for bicycles.',['A) For example,','B) Similarly,','C) However,','D) As a result,'],'C','Investment (positive) vs. low adoption (negative). "However" signals the contrast.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q13','rw1',13,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Text 1: The rise of plant-based meat represents a significant shift in food technology, potentially reducing the environmental footprint of food production.\n\nText 2: While plant-based meats have gained market share, nutritionists caution that these products are often highly processed and may contain more sodium than animal-based counterparts.',['A) They agree plant-based meat is always healthier.','B) Text 2 acknowledges potential benefits while raising nutritional concerns about Text 1\'s products.','C) Text 1 criticizes plant-based meat while Text 2 supports it.','D) Both argue consumers should avoid processed foods.'],'B','Text 2 acknowledges market share (accepting popularity) but raises nutritional concerns. Acknowledges benefits while adding caveats.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q14','rw1',14,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The artist _____ paintings have been exhibited across Europe recently received a prestigious award.',['A) who','B) whose','C) which','D) that'],'B',"'Whose' is the possessive relative pronoun connecting 'artist' to 'paintings.'",'medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q15','rw1',15,'vocab','Words in Context','','The researcher\'s _____ analysis\u2014examining every variable and cross-referencing sources\u2014left no room for doubt.',['A) cursory','B) meticulous','C) biased','D) speculative'],'B',"'Meticulous' means showing great attention to detail, matching 'examining every variable.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q16','rw1',16,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student writing about the discovery of penicillin has notes:\n- 1928: Fleming noticed mold killing bacteria\n- Fleming could not purify the compound\n- 1940: Florey and Chain purified penicillin\n- Mass production during WWII saved countless lives\n- 1945: Nobel Prize shared by all three\n\nThe student wants to emphasize the gap between discovery and medical use.',['A) Fleming discovered penicillin in 1928.','B) Fleming could not purify the compound; it was not until 1940 that Florey and Chain successfully purified penicillin for medical use.','C) Mass production during WWII saved lives.','D) All three shared the 1945 Nobel Prize.'],'B','Shows the 12-year gap between discovery (1928) and purification (1940), emphasizing the development needed.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q17','rw1',17,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Economist Esther Duflo\'s research shows that small, targeted interventions can have outsized effects on poverty. Providing free mosquito nets in Kenya increased usage from 20% to 60%, significantly reducing malaria rates. She argues that evidence-based micro-interventions are more effective than broad policy changes.',['A) To describe malaria in Kenya','B) To argue that small, evidence-based interventions can effectively address poverty','C) To compare different public health approaches','D) To explain why broad policies always fail'],'B','Presents Duflo\'s argument with the net study as evidence. Main purpose is the effectiveness of micro-interventions.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q18','rw1',18,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The symphony, which _____ composed in 1808, is regarded as one of Beethoven\'s greatest works.',['A) was','B) were','C) is','D) has been'],'A','Past tense "was" matches "composed in 1808" (completed past event). "Were" is plural, "is" is present.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q19','rw1',19,'vocab','Words in Context','','The senator\'s speech was filled with _____ rhetoric\u2014stirring imagery that moved the audience but offered little concrete policy.',['A) vapid','B) eloquent','C) hostile','D) technical'],'B',"'Eloquent' means fluent and persuasive, matching 'stirring imagery.' The contrast with 'little concrete policy' suggests style over substance.",'medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q20','rw1',20,'passage','Command of Evidence','','In 2016, Barcelona implemented "superblocks," converting car-filled streets into pedestrian plazas. Studies found noise pollution dropped 25% and NO2 levels decreased significantly in affected areas.',['A) To describe a city planning initiative and its measured outcomes','B) To argue all cities should adopt superblocks','C) To compare Barcelona with other cities','D) To explain why car ownership is declining'],'A','Describes the program and presents measured outcomes (noise, NO2).','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q21','rw1',21,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','Archaeologists believed humans arrived in the Americas 13,000 years ago via a land bridge. _____ discoveries of 16,000-year-old tools in Chile suggest earlier arrival, possibly by coastal routes.',['A) Similarly,','B) However,','C) For example,','D) Therefore,'],'B','Established timeline vs. new evidence. "However" signals the contrast.','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q22','rw1',22,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The new policy, _____ aims to reduce emissions by 40%, has been endorsed by environmental groups.',['A) that','B) which','C) what','D) it'],'B','Nonrestrictive clause (commas). "Which" is correct for nonrestrictive clauses modifying things.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q23','rw1',23,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student writing about sleep deprivation has notes:\n- Adults need 7-9 hours per night\n- Sleep deprivation impairs cognition similar to alcohol\n- Chronic deprivation linked to obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease\n- 1 in 3 American adults doesn\'t get enough sleep\n- Shift workers are disproportionately affected\n\nThe student wants to emphasize the scale of the problem.',['A) Adults need 7-9 hours of sleep.','B) 1 in 3 American adults doesn\'t get enough sleep, and chronic deprivation is linked to obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease.','C) Shift workers are disproportionately affected.','D) Sleep deprivation impairs cognition like alcohol.'],'B','Combines prevalence (1 in 3) with serious health consequences, emphasizing the scale.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q24','rw1',24,'vocab','Words in Context','','The chef\'s _____ approach\u2014combining unexpected ingredients like chocolate and chili\u2014initially surprised diners but won critical acclaim.',['A) conventional','B) unorthodox','C) careless','D) traditional'],'B',"'Unorthodox' means unconventional, matching 'unexpected ingredients' and initial surprise.",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q25','rw1',25,'passage','Command of Evidence','','A 2022 study found that handwriting notes retains more information than typing. Researchers attributed this to handwriting forcing students to process and summarize rather than transcribe verbatim.',['A) Laptop note-taking is always inferior.','B) Handwriting may improve retention because it requires active processing.','C) Students should never use laptops.','D) The journal published a controversial study.'],'B','Presents the finding (handwriting retains more) and the mechanism (active processing vs. transcription).','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q26','rw1',26,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The team of researchers _____ been working on the vaccine for two years before achieving a breakthrough.',['A) has','B) have','C) had','D) having'],'C','Past perfect "had been working" shows action completed before another past action ("achieving").','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q27','rw1',27,'passage','Text Structure and Purpose','','The concept of "food miles"\u2014the distance food travels from farm to plate\u2014has been used to argue that local food is more environmentally friendly. However, a 2020 study found transportation accounts for only 10% of food\'s carbon footprint, while production methods account for over 80%.',['A) It supports the food miles concept.','B) It challenges the food miles concept by showing transportation is a relatively small factor.','C) It explains why local food is always better.','D) It defines carbon footprint.'],'B','The data (10% vs. 80%) challenges the food miles concept that focuses on distance.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q28','rw1',28,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student writing about artificial intelligence has notes:\n- 1950: Turing proposed the Turing Test\n- 1956: "Artificial intelligence" coined at Dartmouth\n- 1997: Deep Blue defeated chess champion Kasparov\n- 2016: AlphaGo defeated Go world champion\n- 2022: Large language models demonstrated human-like text generation\n\nThe student wants to highlight milestones in AI matching human performance.',['A) The term "AI" was coined in 1956.','B) Turing proposed the Turing Test in 1950.','C) From Deep Blue defeating a chess champion in 1997 to AlphaGo winning at Go in 2016, AI has progressively mastered games once thought to require human intelligence.','D) Language models can generate human-like text.'],'C','Connects multiple milestones showing progression in matching human performance.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q29','rw1',29,'vocab','Words in Context','','The documentary filmmaker was known for her _____ style\u2014spending years following subjects, accumulating hundreds of hours of footage.',['A) minimalist','B) immersive','C) controversial','D) conventional'],'B',"'Immersive' means deeply involved, matching 'years following subjects' and 'hundreds of hours.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q30','rw1',30,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The city council _____ three new parks in the downtown area over the past five years.',['A) build','B) builds','C) has built','D) building'],'C','"Over the past five years" continues to the present. Present perfect "has built."','easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q31','rw1',31,'passage','Command of Evidence','','In 2019, Costa Rica generated over 98% of its electricity from renewable sources. The country aims to become fully carbon neutral by 2050, building on decades of environmental policy prioritizing conservation.',['A) It explains why Costa Rica uses hydropower.','B) It provides context for the country\'s renewable achievement by referencing its long-standing commitment.','C) It argues all countries should follow Costa Rica.','D) It compares Costa Rica with other nations.'],'B','The 98% achievement is contextualized by decades of environmental policy, showing long-standing commitment.','medium'),
q('t4_rw1_q32','rw1',32,'vocab','Words in Context','','The committee\'s final report was _____, spanning over 500 pages and covering every aspect of the investigation in exhaustive detail.',['A) brief','B) comprehensive','C) biased','D) vague'],'B',"'Comprehensive' means complete and thorough, matching '500 pages covering every aspect.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw1_q33','rw1',33,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','Deep-sea mining could provide access to valuable minerals. _____ it could disrupt fragile ecosystems that scientists have barely begun to study.',['A) For example,','B) Similarly,','C) However,','D) Therefore,'],'C','Opportunity (minerals) vs. risk (ecosystem disruption). "However" signals the contrast.','easy')
];

const t4rw2 = [
q('t4_rw2_q1','rw2',1,'vocab','Words in Context','','The ambassador remained _____ during heated negotiations, refusing to be provoked by aggressive tactics.',['A) hostile','B) composed','C) confused','D) silent'],'B',"'Composed' means calm and self-controlled, matching 'refusing to be provoked.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q2','rw2',2,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','Astronomers have discovered thousands of exoplanets. A small number orbit within their star\'s habitable zone, _____ liquid water could potentially exist.',['A) which','B) where','C) when','D) why'],'B',"'Where' refers to a place (the habitable zone) and introduces the clause about water existing there.",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q3','rw2',3,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Social media use is correlated with increased anxiety and depression in teenagers. However, researchers caution that correlation does not imply causation\u2014teenagers with existing mental health issues may be more likely to use social media extensively.',['A) To prove social media causes mental health problems','B) To present a correlation while noting that causation has not been established','C) To argue teenagers should stop using social media','D) To explain how platforms are designed'],'B','Presents the correlation but explicitly cautions against assuming causation. B captures both the finding and the caveat.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q4','rw2',4,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','The Great Barrier Reef has experienced five mass bleaching events since 2016. _____ scientists warn that without reduced emissions, the reef could face annual bleaching by 2050.',['A) For example,','B) In other words,','C) As a result,','D) Looking ahead,'],'D','Past events vs. future projections. "Looking ahead" signals the temporal shift to predictions.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q5','rw2',5,'vocab','Words in Context','','The politician\'s _____ promises\u2014offering everything from free healthcare to universal basic income\u2014sounded appealing but lacked implementation plans.',['A) modest','B) sweeping','C) vague','D) honest'],'B',"'Sweeping' means broad and far-reaching, matching the range of promises. The contrast with 'lacking plans' suggests scope over substance.",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q6','rw2',6,'passage','Text Structure and Purpose','','Lab-grown meat\u2014produced by cultivating animal cells rather than raising livestock\u2014could revolutionize food production. Proponents say it reduces emissions and animal suffering. Critics note it is energy-intensive and long-term health effects are unknown.',['A) It introduces a technology and presents arguments from supporters and critics.','B) It argues lab-grown meat is superior.','C) It explains the science of growing meat.','D) It predicts lab-grown meat will replace traditional meat.'],'A','Introduces the technology, presents proponent arguments and critic concerns. Balanced structure.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q7','rw2',7,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The data _____ that air quality has improved since the city implemented its clean air initiative.',['A) suggest','B) suggests','C) suggesting','D) suggested'],'B',"'Data' as a collective noun takes singular verb. 'Suggests' with present tense matches 'has improved.'",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q8','rw2',8,'vocab','Words in Context','','The engineer\'s _____ solution\u2014using recycled materials to reinforce the bridge\u2014saved millions while reducing waste.',['A) impractical','B) ingenious','C) temporary','D) expensive'],'B',"'Ingenious' means clever and inventive, matching a solution with dual benefits (savings and waste reduction).",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q9','rw2',9,'passage','Command of Evidence','','A 2021 study found that people who regularly play instruments have thicker cortical regions associated with auditory processing. The effects were most pronounced in those who began playing before age seven.',['A) It contradicts the study.','B) It provides additional detail refining the finding.','C) It introduces a separate study.','D) It explains methodology.'],'B','Adds nuance: strongest effect in early starters, refining the main finding.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q10','rw2',10,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The museum _____ its collection of contemporary art last year, adding over 200 new works.',['A) expand','B) expands','C) expanded','D) expanding'],'C','"Last year" indicates past tense. "Expanded" is the correct past tense form.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q11','rw2',11,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','The deep ocean contains vast mineral deposits. _____ deep-sea mining could disrupt fragile ecosystems barely studied by scientists.',['A) For example,','B) Similarly,','C) However,','D) Therefore,'],'C','Opportunity (minerals) vs. risk (ecosystem disruption). "However" signals the contrast.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q12','rw2',12,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student researching bilingualism has notes:\n- Bilingual children show enhanced executive function\n- Speaking two languages may delay dementia by 4-5 years\n- Bilingual individuals are better at multitasking\n- Learning a second language improves understanding of one\'s native language\n- Bilingual people may earn higher salaries\n\nThe student wants to emphasize cognitive benefits.',['A) Bilingual people may earn higher salaries.','B) Bilingual children show enhanced executive function, and bilingual individuals tend to be better at multitasking.','C) Learning a second language improves native language understanding.','D) Speaking two languages may delay dementia.'],'B','Combines two cognitive benefits (executive function, multitasking), directly addressing the goal.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q13','rw2',13,'vocab','Words in Context','','The employee\'s _____ attitude\u2014always volunteering for tasks and helping colleagues\u2014quickly made her a team favorite.',['A) indifferent','B) proactive','C) hostile','D) cautious'],'B',"'Proactive' means taking initiative, matching 'always volunteering.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q14','rw2',14,'passage','Command of Evidence','','A 2021 study found that global tree canopy increased by 2.24 million sq km since 1982. However, much of this increase is due to tree plantations, which support far less biodiversity than natural forests.',['A) Natural forests are being replaced by plantations.','B) While tree cover has increased globally, much of the gain lacks biodiversity of natural forests.','C) Tree plantations are better than natural forests.','D) The global canopy has decreased since 1982.'],'B','Presents the increase but qualifies it with the biodiversity concern. B captures both.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q15','rw2',15,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The architect _____ designed the building won several international awards for innovative use of sustainable materials.',['A) who','B) which','C) whose','D) she'],'A',"'Who' introduces a relative clause modifying 'architect' (a person).",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q16','rw2',16,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Herbert Simon coined "satisficing"\u2014choosing the first option meeting minimum criteria rather than searching for the optimal choice. Research shows satisficers tend to be happier than maximizers.',['A) A counterintuitive finding supporting satisficing.','B) Why satisficing is flawed.','C) Definitions of key terms.','D) Research methods used.'],'A','The finding that satisficers are happier is counterintuitive and supports satisficing.','hard'),
q('t4_rw2_q17','rw2',17,'vocab','Words in Context','','The critic described the novel as _____: the plot was inventive but the characters felt flat.',['A) masterful','B) uneven','C) boring','D) original'],'B',"'Uneven' means inconsistent, matching inventive plot vs. flat characters.",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q18','rw2',18,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','If the experiment _____ the expected results, the team will publish their findings.',['A) confirm','B) confirms','C) confirmed','D) will confirm'],'B','In future-conditional if-clauses, present tense is used. "Confirms" agrees with singular "experiment."','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q19','rw2',19,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Economists debate the relationship between minimum wage and employment. Traditional theory suggests raising wages leads to job losses. However, a 1994 study by Card and Krueger found that a minimum wage increase in New Jersey did not lead to significant job losses compared to Pennsylvania.',['A) It presents a theoretical prediction and describes evidence challenging it.','B) It argues minimum wage increases always cause job losses.','C) It compares NJ and PA economies.','D) It explains why traditional theory is always correct.'],'A','Presents theory (wages \u2192 job losses) then describes empirical evidence challenging it (Card-Krueger study).','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q20','rw2',20,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student researching coffee and health has notes:\n- 3-4 cups/day associated with 15% lower cardiovascular disease risk\n- Caffeine temporarily increases blood pressure\n- Coffee contains antioxidants that may reduce inflammation\n- Over 6 cups/day may increase anxiety and disrupt sleep\n- Pregnant women should limit caffeine\n\nThe student wants to emphasize benefits of moderate consumption.',['A) Caffeine increases blood pressure.','B) Drinking 3-4 cups daily is associated with 15% lower cardiovascular risk, and coffee contains antioxidants that may reduce inflammation.','C) Excessive coffee may increase anxiety.','D) Pregnant women should limit caffeine.'],'B','Combines cardiovascular benefit (moderate) with antioxidant benefit, addressing moderate consumption.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q21','rw2',21,'vocab','Words in Context','','The speaker\'s _____ delivery\u2014pausing for effect, varying tone, making eye contact\u2014kept the audience engaged for two hours.',['A) monotone','B) dynamic','C) rushed','D) hesitant'],'B',"'Dynamic' means energetic and engaging, matching the techniques described.",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q22','rw2',22,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The ancient manuscript, _____ origin remains a mystery, was discovered in a cave in Afghanistan.',['A) its','B) it\'s','C) whose','D) which'],'C',"'Whose' is the possessive relative pronoun connecting 'manuscript' to 'origin.'",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q23','rw2',23,'passage','Command of Evidence','','The concept of "degrowth" challenges the assumption that economic growth is always desirable. Proponents argue that in wealthy nations, GDP growth does not necessarily improve well-being and may accelerate environmental destruction. They advocate prioritizing sustainability and quality of life.',['A) To define degrowth and explain its core arguments','B) To argue GDP is the best measure of success','C) To compare degrowth with other theories','D) To explain why wealthy nations should stop growing'],'A','Defines degrowth, presents arguments (GDP \u2260 well-being, environmental harm), and advocacy.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q24','rw2',24,'vocab','Words in Context','','The novelist\'s _____ descriptions\u2014capturing smells, sounds, and textures of rural life\u2014transported readers far from their urban existences.',['A) perfunctory','B) evocative','C) technical','D) somber'],'B',"'Evocative' means vivid and powerful, matching sensory details that transport readers.",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q25','rw2',25,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The teacher asked the students to submit _____ assignments by Friday.',['A) there','B) their','C) they\'re','D) they'],'B',"'Their' is the possessive form of 'they,' modifying 'assignments.'",'easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q26','rw2',26,'passage','Text Structure and Purpose','','Astronomers have discovered thousands of exoplanets. A small number orbit in the habitable zone where liquid water could potentially exist on the surface.',['A) All exoplanets are inhospitable.','B) Among thousands of discovered exoplanets, a small fraction orbit in conditions that could support liquid water.','C) Astronomers have found life on exoplanets.','D) The habitable zone is the only factor for life.'],'B','Presents two facts: thousands discovered, small fraction in habitable zone. B captures both.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q27','rw2',27,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','Among all the students in the advanced class, Priya has demonstrated the _____ understanding of organic chemistry.',['A) strong','B) stronger','C) strongest','D) most strong'],'C','"Among all" compares three or more, requiring superlative "strongest."','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q28','rw2',28,'transition','Expression of Ideas','','Solar energy has become increasingly affordable. The cost of solar panels has dropped 70% since 2010. _____ adoption rates remain low in many regions due to inadequate grid infrastructure.',['A) For example,','B) Similarly,','C) Nevertheless,','D) As a result,'],'C','Lower costs (positive) vs. low adoption (negative). "Nevertheless" signals the contrast.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q29','rw2',29,'passage','Command of Evidence','','A 2023 study found that urban green spaces are associated with lower rates of depression and anxiety. The effect was strongest in low-income neighborhoods, suggesting green spaces may help reduce health disparities.',['A) Urban green spaces are associated with improved mental health, particularly in low-income areas.','B) All neighborhoods should have equal green space.','C) Depression is caused by lack of green space.','D) Low-income neighborhoods have the most parks.'],'A','Presents two findings: green spaces improve mental health, and the effect is strongest in low-income areas.','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q30','rw2',30,'vocab','Words in Context','','The speaker\'s _____ about the economy\u2014acknowledging both strengths and weaknesses\u2014was refreshing compared to the usual partisan rhetoric.',['A) bias','B) candor','C) confusion','D) hostility'],'B',"'Candor' means honest and straightforward, matching 'acknowledging both strengths and weaknesses.'",'medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q31','rw2',31,'notes','Rhetorical Synthesis','','A student researching the internet has notes:\n- 1969: ARPANET connected four university computers\n- 1983: TCP/IP protocol adopted\n- 1991: Tim Berners-Lee created the World Wide Web\n- 1993: Mosaic browser introduced graphical interface\n- 2007: iPhone accelerated mobile internet\n\nThe student wants to highlight how the internet became accessible to the public.',['A) ARPANET connected four computers in 1969.','B) TCP/IP was adopted in 1983.','C) Tim Berners-Lee created the WWW in 1991, and the Mosaic browser in 1993 introduced a graphical interface, making the internet accessible to non-specialists.','D) The iPhone was released in 2007.'],'C','Combines WWW creation (accessible to non-specialists) and graphical browser (easy to use), showing how the internet became public.','medium'),
q('t4_rw2_q32','rw2',32,'grammar','Standard English Conventions','','The number of students in online courses _____ dramatically since the pandemic.',['A) increase','B) increases','C) has increased','D) increasing'],'C','"Since the pandemic" continues to present. Present perfect "has increased."','easy'),
q('t4_rw2_q33','rw2',33,'passage','Command of Evidence','','Psychologist Angela Duckworth\'s research on "grit"\u2014passion and perseverance for long-term goals\u2014shows that grit predicts success better than IQ or talent. In studies of West Point cadets and spelling bee contestants, grittier individuals were more likely to achieve their goals.',['A) IQ is the most important predictor of success.','B) Grit, or sustained passion and perseverance, can be a stronger predictor of success than innate ability.','C) West Point cadets are grittier than spelling bee contestants.','D) Talent is irrelevant to achieving goals.'],'B','Presents Duckworth\'s finding that grit predicts success better than IQ or talent, with evidence from multiple domains.','easy')
];

